05056nam a22007695i 9780674369634DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)900717670  a97806743696347 a10.4159/harvard.97806743696342doi  a(DE-B1597)427270  a(OCoLC)880147753  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHV6248.M278bK93 2014eb 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a364.1/3360922231 aKwass, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aContraband :bLouis Mandrin and the Making of a Global Underground /cMichael Kwass. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (469 p.) :b24 halftones, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Globalization Of European Consumption -- t2. The King Intervenes -- t3. The Making of a Smuggler -- t4. The Shadow Economy -- t5. Rebel Rebel -- t6. Triumph -- t7. The Would- Be General -- t8. Captured -- t9. The Execution of Louis Mandrin -- t10. Mandrin into Print -- t11. Smuggling in the Enlightenment -- t12. Revolution -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLouis Mandrin led a gang of bandits who brazenly smuggled contraband into eighteenth-century France. Michael Kwass brings new life to the legend of this Gallic Robin Hood and the thriving underworld he helped to create. Decades before the storming of the Bastille, surging world trade excited a revolution in consumption that transformed the French kingdom. Contraband exposes the dark side of this early phase of globalization, revealing hidden connections between illicit commerce, criminality, and popular revolt. France's economic system was tailor-made for an enterprising outlaw like Mandrin. As French subjects began to crave colonial products, Louis XIV lined the royal coffers by imposing a state monopoly on tobacco from America and an embargo on brilliantly colored calico cloth from India. Vigorous black markets arose through which traffickers fed these exotic goods to eager French consumers. Flouting the law with unparalleled panache, Mandrin captured widespread public attention to become a symbol of a defiant underground. This furtive economy generated violent clashes between gangs of smugglers and customs agents in the borderlands. Eventually, Mandrin was captured by French troops and put to death in a brutal public execution intended to demonstrate the king's absolute authority. But the spectacle only cemented Mandrin's status as a rebel folk hero in an age of mounting discontent. Amid cycles of underground rebellion and agonizing penal repression, the memory of Mandrin inspired ordinary subjects and Enlightenment philosophers alike to challenge royal power and forge a movement for radical political change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCriminalsxBiographyxFrance. 0aCriminalszFrancevBiography. 0aSmugglersxBiographyxFrance. 0aSmugglerszFrancevBiography. 0aSmugglingxHistoryx18th centuryxFrance. 0aSmugglingzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2014z9783110370225oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067436963440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674369634423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674369634.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press C